<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-719-426  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 719 426.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDGE on andamp; about ATandamp;T  June 25, 1990 v5 n100 p6(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EDGE Publishing 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber-to-the-curb: Pac Bell to test Raynet technology. Not thelast &quot;last-mile&quot; test. (Raynet's Loop Optical Carrier)(illustration)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Pacific Bell (communication systems)Raynet Corp. (communication systems).andO;Topic:     Telephone SystemsFiber OpticsTestingTelecommunications.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>FIBER-TO-THE-CURB: PAC BELL TO TEST RAYNET TECHNOLOGY.andM;NOT THE LAST &quot;LAST-MILE&quot; TESTandM;Pacific Bell will test Raynet's new fiber-to-the-curb technology as apotentially cost-effective alternative to traditional copper wires forproviding residential telephone service.andM;The technology test of Raynet's LOC (Loop Optical Carrier) system will beconducted this month among 142 Raynet employees on the company's Menlo Parkcampus who will use a Centrex-based, fiber-optic network for telephoneservice and low-speed data transmission.andM;Fiber-optic systems, which transmit voice and data as encoded streams oflaser light, have demonstrated significant benefits in capacity, signalquality and dependability.andP;  Until now, however, the cost of these systems wasjustifiable only for dense, high-volume applications, such as transmission oflong-distance telephone service, high-speed computer data and studio-qualityvideo.andM;Pacific Bell will be evaluating the LOC system as a means of bringing thebenefits of fiber optics into the &quot;last mile&quot; of the telephone network.andP;  In aresidential setting, the optical fiber system would provide service from adistribution terminal serving a neighborhood to pedestals along the curb.andO;Each pedestal would be connected to several homes via traditional metallictelephone lines.andM;The same architecture will be replicated in the Menlo Park test where thesystem will serve Raynet employees in five buildings.andM;Raynet's system is one of several fiber-loop systems Pacific Bell plans toexplore for potential applications in the residential telephone marketplace.andM;Key Executives: Geoff Cullimore, Pacific Bell director of customer premisesbroadband operations.andP;  Ed Davis, president and chief executive officer ofRaynet.andO;</TEXT></DOC>